We recommended that:

Management create an Inventory Committee that will take charge in the conduct a complete inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality and thereafter the preparation of the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;



The Municipal Treasury Office prepare a LRN Map and a Report on the LRN at the end of every accounting period;


The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of the road components for road projects; 
The Municipal Accountant:

Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation of each depreciable LRN component;


Maintain subsidiary ledgers for the Road Network and their components; and


Provide adequate disclosure for the total Road Network System in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:

Conduct project inspection at 95 percent completion, as suggested by the Revised IRR, considering its practicability, or, at the target project completion date when such was not yet achieved, to determine actual accomplishment to come up with a reliable and accurate amount of delay;

Observe strictly the guidelines in the implementation of infrastructure contracts stated in the Revised IRR, taking emphasis on the computation of target and revised completion dates so as not to incur loss on the failure to bill liquidated damages when justified by the condition.

We recommended that Management:

Generate Allowance for Impairment for the receivables account so as to present fairly the proper valuation of their net realizable value, and, adjust its effect to the equity account;


Investigate the status of high probability of uncertainty of collection and, if warranted, initiate request for write-off to COA as per COA Circular 2016-005, Guidelines and Procedures on Write-Off of Receivables.

Recommendation/s:
a) For the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Officer, in the preparation of the reports to document the LDRRMF transactions, abide by and observe the reporting guidelines of COA Circular No. 2012-002;
b) For the Municipal Accountant to:
i. Take the necessary accounting entries to record the deficiency in the transferred amount in the General and Trust Fund books;
ii. Include in the Notes to Financial Statements, for the following years, a disclosure of the unutilized balance of LDRRMF in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-002; and,
iii. Ensure that all entries in the Financial Statements reconcile with their supporting reports and records.

Recommendation/s:
a) Provide, in every contract, a provision on liquidated damages, in accordance with the requirement of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
b) Conduct project inspection at 95 percent completion, as suggested by the Revised IRR, considering its practicability, or, at the target project completion date when such was not yet achieved, to determine actual accomplishment to come up with a reliable and accurate amount of delay;
c) Observe strictly the guidelines in the implementation of infrastructure contracts stated in the Revised IRR, taking emphasis on the computation of target and revised completion dates so as not to incur loss on the failure to bill liquidated damages when justified by the condition.

Recommendation/s:
a) Strictly implement the provisions of the IRR of R.A. No. 9184 by requiring the bidder/contractor to submit the complete infrastructure documents to ascertain: (a) relevance of the approval of requests for suspension of work and extension of contract time; and (b) compliance to the required specifications in the contract of the projects;
b) Ensure that, prior to granting suspension of work and extension of contract time, (1) the grounds for requests for suspensions are among those enumerated in the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, (2) requests for extension of contract time are supported with a written consent of the bondsman, and (3) requests are justified by the circumstances via an investigation/determination of its applicability.

Recommendation/s:
a) Generate Allowance for Impairment for the receivables account so as to present fairly the proper valuation of their net realizable value, and, adjust its effect to the equity account;
b) Investigate the status of high probability of uncertainty of collection and, if warranted, initiate request for write-off to COA as per COA Circular 2016-005, Guidelines and Procedures on Write-Off of Receivables.

We reiterated the following prior years’ recommendations:

Require personnel concerned to present the property to the Inventory Team/PO and the latter to report status to the Audit Team; 

Immediately process cases of loss of PPE in accordance with the prescribed procedures.  Further, require the accountable employees who cannot show reasonable justification to pay the sound value of the property lost;


Document the alleged donations and/or transfers; and



Determine persons immediately accountable for property items which cannot be located through the issued Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE). Ascertain their status and, if applicable, process them as cases of loss in accordance with prescribed procedures.

We recommended the management to:

Ensure that no additional cash advance shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous ones granted to him is first fully liquidated and accounted for in the books of accounts;

Instruct the payroll officer to consolidate cash advances in one request so long as it does exceed the officer’s cash accountability;

Implement the policy that all cash advances shall be fully liquidated at the end of each year and refund any unexpended balances to the cashier/collecting officer for the issuance of receipt in accordance with 4.1.3 (xi) of COA Circular No. 2009-002.

We have recommended that management:

Require the employees accountable for the property claimed to be unserviceable to return the same to the supply officer for disposal;



Prepare the IIRUP to document the status of these allegedly defective, destroyed, and non-functional property and equipment.

We recommended that management:

Require personnel concerned to present property and equipment to the inventory team/property officer and the latter to report status to the Audit Team; 

Immediately process cases of loss of PPE in accordance with the prescribed procedures.  Further, require the accountable employees who cannot show reasonable justification to pay the sound value of the property lost;

Document the alleged donations, transfers, and sale; and,




Determine persons immediately accountable for property items, which cannot be located through the issued Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE).
